Welcome to the=C2=A01,977=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined=
 us since last Monday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0160,388=
 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:=20
=F0=9F=8E=A7=C2=A0 For the audio version, click the play button or listen o=
n Spotify [ https://substack.com/redirect/f10509c6-64f0-4778-9d3e-641bfc946=
327?r=3D9p0gt ] or=C2=A0Apple Podcasts [ https://substack.com/redirect/6564=
0555-4384-4117-9195-0203aeffc070?r=3D9p0gt ]
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring, the whole thing, is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 =
Formic [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5ff6d39-e065-48dd-822e-c46f2dfb2721=
?r=3D9p0gt ]
Formic [ https://substack.com/redirect/93ec02e9-5d27-4c5f-a754-2f9fafd9b3e8=
?r=3D9p0gt ] delivers Robots by the Hour to manufacturers. It=E2=80=99s mak=
ing small and medium American businesses stronger, fighting inflation, and =
creating abundance. If you want to help bring about an abundant future =E2=
=80=94 or if you just really want to work with cutting edge robots =E2=80=
=94 good news: Formic is hiring [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5ff6d39-e0=
65-48dd-822e-c46f2dfb2721?r=3D9p0gt ].
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Monday! The Phillies are heading to the World Series. What a way to k=
ick the week into gear. Speaking of kicking things into gear=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve been reading Not Boring this year, you=E2=80=99ll know th=
at I=E2=80=99ve become obsessed with the idea of abundance. Specifically, I=
 believe that technology can push humanity forward and produce a higher sta=
ndard of living for everyone. This idea has been the topic of essays like O=
ptimism [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e1d4af5-e31b-4de3-a460-5dea152268d=
5?r=3D9p0gt ], Working Harder and Smarter [ https://substack.com/redirect/6=
3fad152-a1b6-4fb2-803b-26fb2d070d14?r=3D9p0gt ], and The Invisible Hand=E2=
=80=99s Visible Swarm [ https://substack.com/redirect/fda67c59-e83b-4b16-8d=
0a-b0be51ace82f?r=3D9p0gt ].=C2=A0
Of course, looking around, it=E2=80=99s hard to get super excited right now=
=2E There=E2=80=99s inflation, war, clima=
te change, and looming recession. We=
 have no flying cars. Maybe it=E2=80=99s my optimism speaking, but I firmly=
 believe that the cavalry is coming =E2=80=93 in the form of abundant renew=
able energy, biotech breakthroughs, and much more. I unabashedly root for t=
he Hard Startups [ https://substack.com/redirect/7dcff299-4032-4246-9463-2f=
4c337ce1b6?r=3D9p0gt ] building solutions to our biggest challenges.=C2=A0
So when Garry Tan [ https://substack.com/redirect/f98093bf-0851-4b3c-bf38-4=
1df45817385?r=3D9p0gt ], now the President of Y Combinator, reached out to =
tell me that there was a founder I had to meet, Saman Farid [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/46471763-3266-403f-af85-7e385b8d0017?r=3D9p0gt ], who was =
building a really interesting American manufacturing robotics company calle=
d Formic [ https://substack.com/redirect/93ec02e9-5d27-4c5f-a754-2f9fafd9b3=
e8?r=3D9p0gt ], I jumped at the introduction.=C2=A0
Formic doesn=E2=80=99t make robots. It makes it easy for manufacturers to a=
dopt robots. Given the huge gap between their potential impact and actual d=
eployment, I think it=E2=80=99s the most important part of the stack. If Fo=
rmic succeeds, we=E2=80=99ll manufacture more, better things, more cheaply,=
 in the US.
This essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive. I haven=E2=80=99t put many of these in=
 the Monday slot, but I think that Formic is a company you need to know abo=
ut, and that fits so well into Not Boring=E2=80=99s main themes that it des=
erves to be the main event. You can read more about how I choose which comp=
anies to do deep dives on, and how I write them here [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/aa3b85f3-255b-4234-9fbe-8830fc5074b4?r=3D9p0gt ].
Now throw this on to get in the mood:=C2=A0
And let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Formic: Automating Abundance
The goal is abundance.
We want more and better things, more cheaply. We want those things to be ma=
de closer to home. We want less fragile supply chains, so that those things=
 are always available when we need them. We want more good jobs, and more t=
ime unlocked to maximize our human potential.=C2=A0
Over the long-term, there are a lot of things we can do to create abundance=
=2E Generate clean, cheap, renewable elec=
tricity. Improve the education syste=
m. Build more houses. Change laws.
In the immediate term, the answer is robots.
No, not those robots, at least not yet. These robots.
Automating parts of the manufacturing process with robots is no longer a sc=
i-fi-ish nice-to-have. With 10.1 million unfilled jobs in America as of Aug=
ust, inflation running rampant, supply chains breaking everywhere, and resh=
oring of manufacturing, robots are a necessity. As Noah Smith wrote in Amer=
ican workers need lots and lots of robots [ https://substack.com/redirect/7=
285cd1c-af49-4e41-99c4-80b296540b5f?r=3D9p0gt ]:=C2=A0
If we really want to change our economy in all the ways we=E2=80=99ve been =
hoping =E2=80=94 reshoring manufacturing from China, securing supply chains=
, preventing inflationary bottlenecks, and so on =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99re go=
ing to need quite a lot of automation. Indeed, if the progressive project i=
s to be revived in America, it will need robots to carry it forward.
Robots also happen to be very good for the businesses that employ them, exp=
anding shifts, reducing turnover hassles, and increasing profits.
It=E2=80=99s hard to think of an industry with stronger tailwinds than robo=
tic automation:
Improving AI/ML. Robots can do more complex things better now than they cou=
ld just a few years ago, and will continue to improve at a rapid clip from =
here on out.
Labor Shortages. As of August, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reported [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/75edf5b7-149c-46b4-b9fa-32fd0d585970?r=3D9p0gt =
] that there were 10.1 million unfilled jobs in America, of which about 1.5=
 million are in manufacturing.
Inflation. Things are getting more expensive across the board, and labor co=
sts are a big piece of the puzzle. According to the BLS [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/0a6dd67a-7efb-46b3-863c-0ae903e0aa82?r=3D9p0gt ], private indu=
stry labor costs rose 5.5% over the 12 months ending June 2022, after risin=
g 3.1% in the 12 months prior.=C2=A0
Supply Chains Breaking. Due to a combination of labor shortages, component =
shortages, shipping, and more, broken supply chains and delayed products ar=
e a fact of life in post-COVID America.=C2=A0
Reshoring American Manufacturing. After decades of globalization, America i=
s bringing manufacturing back home. As that plays out, there will be even m=
ore jobs that need to be filled (and higher prices at American wages, all e=
lse equal).=C2=A0
Rising Geopolitical Tensions. The Biden Administration recently dealt a blo=
w to China=E2=80=99s chip manufacturing efforts, the latest move in an ongo=
ing trade war between the two powers. It=E2=80=99s hard to imagine that Chi=
na =E2=80=93 from whom we bought an all-time high $50 billion worth of good=
s in August according to the US Census Bureau [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/398ac574-1ee6-4133-9375-20046f933c4c?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=93 won=E2=80=99t=
 retaliate.
There are more. In my piece on Hadrian [ https://substack.com/redirect/5a17=
6ad2-35c2-41e2-9cff-d37b02613aec?r=3D9p0gt ], we covered the aging manufact=
uring base, and the fact that the next generation either can=E2=80=99t or d=
oesn=E2=80=99t want to take over the family business. Thanks to a cocktail =
of COVID and politics, US immigration has been declining since a peak in ea=
rly 2016 [ https://substack.com/redirect/0fe3f458-a907-4707-9238-c9078c2150=
e5?r=3D9p0gt ].=C2=A0
All to say, robots are no longer some futuristic technology that only autom=
akers and avant garde companies like Amazon can afford to play with. Robots=
 are a necessity if we want to maintain our standard of living, and do so a=
t affordable prices.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not (or shouldn=E2=80=99t be) controversial to suggest that we=
=E2=80=99re going to need, and get, a lot more robots in the coming years. =
Manufacturing Digital [ https://substack.com/redirect/ec9bd3a7-3b2d-4186-ac=
97-b9c6855d09b9?r=3D9p0gt ] projects that the manufacturing robotics market=
 will more than double from $24.3 billion in 2022 to $52.8 billion in 2026.
The big strategic question is: what=E2=80=99s the best way to ride those ta=
ilwinds and accelerate deployment?=C2=A0
One way is direct: make the thing. In this case, make robots. A flood of co=
mpanies are building robots with all sorts of capabilities, and driving qua=
lity up and hardware prices down.=C2=A0
A second is to sell picks & shovels. Make the things that go into making th=
e robots. From software to fixturing to vision systems, startups and incumb=
ents alike are creating new inputs, again improving quality and lowering co=
sts.=C2=A0
A third way is to sit on top of all of the hustle and bustle and competitio=
n below, to abstract all of that complexity away and just give customers ex=
actly what they want, wrapped in a bow: as-a-service.
Formic [ https://substack.com/redirect/93ec02e9-5d27-4c5f-a754-2f9fafd9b3e8=
?r=3D9p0gt ] is taking the third path, delivering Robots by the Hour to cus=
tomers who don=E2=80=99t care who makes the robot or how, just that the job=
 gets done well. Their customers don=E2=80=99t even want robots, really, th=
ey want reliable labor. That=E2=80=99s what Formic gives them.=C2=A0
The model, and the company, is the brainchild of Saman Farid [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/e3409d1e-68da-4010-8784-7077ffd154bf?r=3D9p0gt ] and Misa=
 Ilkhechi [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae087b16-c10c-4895-86ce-b40d55277=
17d?r=3D9p0gt ]. Misa=E2=80=99s LinkedIn model puts the societal value prop=
osition clearly: Robots =3D Unlimited Labor.
Saman grew up in factories after his dad moved the family to Beijing when h=
e was six-years-old. After an Engineering degree from The Cooper Union, Sam=
an got his MBA from a joint program between MIT and China=E2=80=99s Tsinghu=
a University. He=E2=80=99s spent most of his professional life building and=
 investing at the intersection of AI/ML and the real world.=C2=A0
Garry Tan [ https://substack.com/redirect/f98093bf-0851-4b3c-bf38-41df45817=
385?r=3D9p0gt ], the Y Combinator President who led Formic=E2=80=99s Seed r=
ound while at Initialized Capital, explained how Saman=E2=80=99s background=
 led to Formic:
Saman is a very special example of someone who has seen things most people =
don't see, and then has followed his intuition to figure out what society, =
at many levels, needs. His experience with China is relevant, since America=
n vibrance is predicated on strong manufacturing, and automation is the key=
stone to that.
Specifically, he saw what embracing automation could do to boost an economy=
=2E =E2=80=9CIn China from the 1980s to t=
he 2000s, I saw the impact of rapid =
and massive industrialization. When I moved to the US, I saw the same thing=
 happening in reverse: legacy institutions, particularly industrial ones, w=
ere starting to crumble.=E2=80=9D
As an investor at Baidu Ventures, and a board member at multiple robotics c=
ompanies, he saw first-hand that robotic automation was a thing, that the t=
echnology works, and that robots have a great ROI. He also saw that no one =
outside of Silicon Valley and Detroit was deploying them.
Formic was born to address that deployment gap. It=E2=80=99s not building a=
 new, technically superior robot =E2=80=93 there are plenty of brilliant mi=
nds working on those, and competitive dynamics are quickly commoditizing th=
at layer =E2=80=93 but a suite of software, financial products, and service=
s designed to get all of those robots deployed en masse. Saman told me that=
 Formic wants to =E2=80=9Cbuild the world=E2=80=99s largest robotic workfor=
ce.=E2=80=9D
It=E2=80=99s early, but the model is working. Founded in 2020 and launched =
in August 2021, Formic has 50+ robots in various stages of deployment, and =
has grown its revenue 12x year-over-year. For a sense of scale, the largest=
 purchasers in the country buy about 250-300 robots. One more 12x and they=
=E2=80=99re buying more robots than anyone.=C2=A0
Importantly, Formic is doing more than riding tailwinds; it=E2=80=99s expan=
ding the market. Manufacturers that wouldn=E2=80=99t have deployed robots b=
efore Formic are finally automating because the company exists. Formic=E2=
=80=99s customers include companies that make metal parts for car chassis, =
aluminum parts for planes, chocolate chip cookies, shredded lettuce that en=
ds up in KFC / Taco Bell, plastic parts for lawn mowers and golf carts, Mat=
cha and protein powder, and spare parts for agricultural equipment. One cus=
tomer, Polar, has been around so long that it used to make parts for the Fo=
rd Model T. The list demonstrates both the breadth of the robots=E2=80=99 c=
apabilities and Formic=E2=80=99s focus on a few beachhead categories, which=
 we=E2=80=99ll explore.
And Formic is well-capitalized to expand. In March 2021, Tan=E2=80=99s Init=
ialized Capital led a $5.5 million Seed round. In January 2022, Lux Capital=
=E2=80=99s Shahin Farschi led a $26.5 million Series A. In between, the com=
pany put in place $150 million of debt facilities, a critical component of =
Formic=E2=80=99s business model, to fund expansion.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ll go into that business model, and much more, to unpack automat=
ion and Formic=E2=80=99s role in the ecosystem:
The Rise of the Robots=C2=A0
Formic: Unlimited-Labor-as-a-Service
Formic=E2=80=99s Business Model
Robotic Powers
Automating Abundance=C2=A0
But first, a little bit more on the robots. To root for Formic as hard as y=
ou should, you need to understand why more robots =3D unequivocally good.
Those gifs took up a lot of email space! (Worth it). To read the full post=
